│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs due to an assertion in GenericLoopInfo::getSubLoops()        │
│ stating that a Loop is not in a valid state. This implies that a Loop object  │
│ being traversed has been marked invalid (Loop::markAsInvalid()) due to prior  │
│ IR modifications, but is still being used by later code.                      │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The opt log shows:                                                            │
│ - LoopSimplify created a dedicated exit block.                                │
│ - LoopUnrollAndJam completely unrolled-and-jammed loop %do.body2.             │
│ - Then the pass crashes in appendReversedLoopsToWorklist while building a     │
│ worklist for loops.                                                           │
│ The pipeline is                                                               │
│ loop(invalidate<all>,loop-unroll-and-jam,loop-unroll-and-jam). The first      │
│ LoopUnrollAndJam pass modifies the loop nest (fully unrolling the middle      │
│ loop). The second invocation then attempts to build a traversal from a        │
│ LoopNest, and crashes.                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ The stack trace points to:                                                    │
│ - llvm::appendReversedLoopsToWorklist(reverse(Loops), Worklist)               │
│ - where Loops = LN.getLoops() from the LoopNest analysis.                     │
│ The assertion triggers when calling L->begin()/end(), which internally checks │
│ the loop's validity. This typically happens when a Loop object has been       │
│ invalidated after structural changes but a stale LoopNest still references    │
│ it.                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In LoopUnrollAndJamPass::run, after performing transformations, the pass      │
│ unconditionally preserves LoopNestAnalysis:                                   │
│   auto PA = getLoopPassPreservedAnalyses();                                   │
│   PA.preserve<LoopNestAnalysis>();                                            │
│   return PA;                                                                  │
│ However, LoopUnrollAndJam modifies the loop structure (e.g., fully unrolling  │
│ jammed loops). Preserving LoopNestAnalysis in that case is incorrect because  │
│ the cached LoopNest will reference old Loop objects that may have been        │
│ invalidated. When the second loop-unroll-and-jam pass runs, it reuses this    │
│ preserved LoopNest, leading to traversal of invalid Loop objects and the      │
│ assertion failure in getSubLoops/end().                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ Thus, the first transformation (complete unroll-and-jam of %do.body2)         │
│ invalidates the loop nest, and the incorrect preservation of LoopNestAnalysis │
│ causes a stale LN to be used by the subsequent pass invocation.               │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopUnrollAndJamPass.cpp                   │
│ - Lines: 465-466                                                              │
│ - Change: Do not preserve LoopNestAnalysis when the pass made modifications.  │
│ Either remove the preservation entirely or guard it so that it is only        │
│ preserved when the function is unmodified (in which case the code already     │
│ returns PreservedAnalyses::all()).                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ Concretely, remove:                                                           │
│   PA.preserve<LoopNestAnalysis>();                                            │
│ so that the returned PreservedAnalyses from getLoopPassPreservedAnalyses()    │
│ does not include LoopNestAnalysis, forcing it to be recomputed for the next   │
│ pass invocation.                                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ This ensures the next pass builds a fresh LoopNest reflecting the updated     │
│ LoopInfo and avoids traversing invalid Loop objects.                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is caused by erroneously preserving LoopNestAnalysis after loop     │
│ transformations in LoopUnrollAndJamPass::run. Removing the preservation of    │
│ LoopNestAnalysis when changes occur will force recomputation of the loop nest │
│ and prevent traversal of invalid Loop objects, fixing the assertion. This     │
│ aligns with the principle that assertion failures indicate earlier logical    │
│ errors—in this case, incorrect analysis preservation after IR/loop structural │
│ changes.                                                                      │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
